The other two Answers are correct, [here](https://stackoverflow.com/a/67117203/642706) &amp; [here](https://stackoverflow.com/a/67117203/642706). 

But if you are using the full name of the person in this way, consider writing a class. If you are using the full name like this in other places, then even more reason to make a class.

In Java 16 and later, you might choose to use the new [record][1] feature to more briefly define the class. Use a record where the primary purpose is to communicate data, transparently and immutably. The compiler implicitly creates the constructor, getters, `equals` &amp; `hashCode`, and `toString`.

    record FullName ( String firstName , String lastName ) {}

So your `Person` class would look like this.

```java
class Person{
    private FullName name;
    private BigDecimal gpa;
    private int age;
}
```

