The `javax.swing.SwingWorker#SwingWorker` is using a `java.util.concurrent.FutureTask` to execute the work provided in the method `doInBackground`.

In `java.util.concurrent.FutureTask#run` we can see that any exceptions are `caught`, and set as the result state of the `FutureTask` via `setException`:

```java
try {
	result = c.call();
	ran = true;
} catch (Throwable ex) {
	result = null;
	ran = false;
	setException(ex);
}
```

So in effect, this means that there are no uncaught exceptions bubbeling up from the executor Threads, and thus it&#39;s logical that your `DefaultUncaughtExceptionHandler` is not used.

You&#39;re going to have to add your own exception handling to the worker, for that you can see the following references:
- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6523623/graceful-exception-handling-in-swing-worker
- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/791223/how-should-i-handle-exceptions-when-using-swingworker
- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/32445902/the-proper-way-to-handle-exceptions-thrown-by-the-swingworker-doinbackground
- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13941236/swingworker-exceptions-lost-even-when-using-wrapper-classes

There are a few options from these references:
- directly handle the exception in your worker, or
- add a property change listener to check when the task is done; `javax.swing.SwingWorker#addPropertyChangeListener`
- and then retrieve the execution result of the task via `javax.swing.SwingWorker#get()` or `javax.swing.SwingWorker#get(long, java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit)`

